<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-409-609  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 409 609.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  Sept 10 1990 v36 n1826 p7(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Commerce loosens export reins. (the US Commerce Department'sBureau of Export Administration's controls on semiconductormanufacturing equipment)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Connelly, Joanne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The US Commerce Department Bureau of Export Administration changesits export controls involving semiconductor manufacturingequipment following high-level meetings of the CoordinatingCommittee for Multilateral Export Controls (CoCom) in Jun 1990.andO;Some low-level and midrange semiconductor production equipmentexported to Eastern Europe and the Soviet Union is completelydecontrolled, including diffusion furnaces, wire bonders and allequipment used for manufacturing printed circuit boards.andP;  Ionimplant equipment and other such midrange devices can now beexported to the Soviet Union up to the so-called China Green Line,but etch, chemical vapor deposition, high-end test and lithographyequipment exports are still tightly controlled.andP;  The Bushadministration is trying to revamp the US export control policy,scrapping Cocom's control lists and basing the new one on militarycritical priorities.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ExportGovernment RegulationPolitical IssuesEastern EuropeSoviet UnionSemiconductor production equipmentCoordinating Committee for Multilateral Export ControlsUnited States. Department of CommerceSemiconductor industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>